WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.278 --> 00:00:01.111
(grinding electric guitar)
- What did you think

00:00:01.111 --> 00:00:01.976
when you saw him coming up with it?

00:00:01.976 --> 00:00:03.037
- Oh, well he was telling us

00:00:03.037 --> 00:00:05.140
that it wasn't loaded, so that was okay.

00:00:05.140 --> 00:00:07.630
- I think he says it
is, is the gun loaded?

00:00:07.630 --> 00:00:09.120
- [Woman] No, he said it wa--

00:00:09.120 --> 00:00:10.960
- No, my gun's got ammo in it.

00:00:10.960 --> 00:00:13.170
We carry it like the police carry it.

00:00:13.170 --> 00:00:14.228
- But you're not the police.

00:00:14.228 --> 00:00:15.061
- [Woman] But you're not, yeah.

00:00:15.061 --> 00:00:16.200
- Well, that's just it, there's really

00:00:16.200 --> 00:00:17.730
no distinction between the police

00:00:17.730 --> 00:00:19.100
and the citizenship other than their

00:00:19.100 --> 00:00:21.890
general training and permits to do so.

00:00:21.890 --> 00:00:23.040
- [Jordan] Training, though, is one thing.

00:00:23.040 --> 00:00:24.520
Why keep it loaded right now?

00:00:24.520 --> 00:00:27.550
- Because if somebody,
an Islamic terrorist,

00:00:27.550 --> 00:00:28.850
whatnot, crazy guy--

00:00:28.850 --> 00:00:30.250
- [Jordan] Islamic terrorist?

00:00:30.250 --> 00:00:31.210
What's your expectation?

00:00:31.210 --> 00:00:32.630
Do you fear that's gonna happen right now?

00:00:32.630 --> 00:00:33.463
- No.

00:00:33.463 --> 00:00:34.296
- Just cause you're walking around

00:00:34.296 --> 00:00:35.790
with a gun on your side
don't make me safe.

00:00:35.790 --> 00:00:37.817
It just doesn't look right, in society.

00:00:37.817 --> 00:00:39.780
- And to be fair, you're passing this out

00:00:39.780 --> 00:00:41.590
because you want more rights because

00:00:41.590 --> 00:00:42.423
you feel you're not--

00:00:42.423 --> 00:00:44.310
- [Man With Gun] I want a
greater restoration of rights.

00:00:44.310 --> 00:00:45.590
- So you don't have enough?

00:00:45.590 --> 00:00:46.730
You're walking around a parade route

00:00:46.730 --> 00:00:48.700
like John Wick and you
feel like, "I want more."

00:00:48.700 --> 00:00:51.090
- That is me, Jordan Klepper, at a parade

00:00:51.090 --> 00:00:52.420
in Gonzalez, Texas.

00:00:52.420 --> 00:00:53.790
I am facilitating a conversation

00:00:53.790 --> 00:00:55.370
between a concerned parade-goer

00:00:55.370 --> 00:00:57.440
and an open carry gun rights activist.

00:00:57.440 --> 00:00:59.860
They were carrying their
guns, out in the open,

00:00:59.860 --> 00:01:02.020
they were big guns, and
they were advocating

00:01:02.020 --> 00:01:04.350
for the idea of constitutional carry.

00:01:04.350 --> 00:01:06.450
And across the state
in Dallas was my friend

00:01:06.450 --> 00:01:08.050
Kobi Libii, and he was with a group

00:01:08.050 --> 00:01:11.210
called Guerrilla Mainframe,
and they are a group

00:01:11.210 --> 00:01:13.550
of black activists who
are drawing attention

00:01:13.550 --> 00:01:15.260
to the cause of police violence

00:01:15.260 --> 00:01:17.370
towards the African-American community.

00:01:17.370 --> 00:01:18.620
We decided to go out on this day

00:01:18.620 --> 00:01:20.110
to see how people reacted to both

00:01:20.110 --> 00:01:21.827
of these groups, to see if race

00:01:21.827 --> 00:01:24.301
played into this at all.

00:01:24.301 --> 00:01:27.120
Spoiler alert, it does.

00:01:27.120 --> 00:01:29.240
It's a really interesting episode for us,

00:01:29.240 --> 00:01:31.200
and I'm inviting my friend Kobi Libii

00:01:31.200 --> 00:01:32.033
on to talk about it.

00:01:32.033 --> 00:01:33.360
We both had different experiences

00:01:33.360 --> 00:01:35.410
but we were making one show, and we saw

00:01:35.410 --> 00:01:37.770
some of these things from
different perspectives,

00:01:37.770 --> 00:01:39.100
it wasn't always easy.

00:01:39.100 --> 00:01:41.430
One state, two protests and a conversation

00:01:41.430 --> 00:01:43.770
around guns and racism in America.

00:01:43.770 --> 00:01:44.939
This is Klepper.

00:01:44.939 --> 00:01:45.772
(lighthearted guitar music)

00:01:45.772 --> 00:01:48.950
- I'm always to get
rid of the shock factor

00:01:48.950 --> 00:01:49.783
of seeing a gun.

00:01:49.783 --> 00:01:51.517
I think people have been conditioned

00:01:51.517 --> 00:01:52.924
"Oh gosh, there's a guy with a gun,

00:01:52.924 --> 00:01:54.570
"I'm gonna call 911."

00:01:54.570 --> 00:01:55.890
- That's a good condition.

00:01:55.890 --> 00:01:56.750
- Well, is it?

00:01:56.750 --> 00:01:59.210
When I see somebody going to church

00:01:59.210 --> 00:02:00.907
I don't call the police
to say "Hey, they're

00:02:00.907 --> 00:02:02.910
"exercising their First Amendment rights."

00:02:02.910 --> 00:02:04.390
- Yeah, well, people aren't getting killed

00:02:04.390 --> 00:02:06.210
with churches all around the country.

00:02:06.210 --> 00:02:08.250
- Some people are getting
killed in churches.

00:02:08.250 --> 00:02:09.870
- Yeah, with guns!

00:02:09.870 --> 00:02:12.590
C.J. is the founder of Open Carry Texas,

00:02:12.590 --> 00:02:13.930
a group that wants to normalize

00:02:13.930 --> 00:02:16.130
the sight of people
carrying guns into Chipotle

00:02:16.130 --> 00:02:18.890
and loosen Texas gun laws.

00:02:18.890 --> 00:02:21.292
They've been effective, in 2016 OCT

00:02:21.292 --> 00:02:23.200
successfully lobbied the state

00:02:23.200 --> 00:02:25.620
to legalized licensed
open carry of handguns.

00:02:25.620 --> 00:02:26.620
- [C.J.] Are we done?

00:02:26.620 --> 00:02:27.453
- [All] No!

00:02:28.498 --> 00:02:30.550
- [Jordan] And today C.J. and 30

00:02:30.550 --> 00:02:32.748
of his OCT buddies are headed to a parade

00:02:32.748 --> 00:02:35.520
in Gonzalez, Texas to spread the word.

00:02:35.520 --> 00:02:37.490
Because this is Texas,
where the state bird

00:02:37.490 --> 00:02:40.450
is a revolver, OCT isn't even the only

00:02:40.450 --> 00:02:43.540
activist group open carrying today.

00:02:43.540 --> 00:02:46.870
250 miles north a second,
totally unrelated group

00:02:46.870 --> 00:02:49.550
is using guns to draw
attention to their cause.

00:02:49.550 --> 00:02:51.910
My friend Kobi Libii
is embedding with them.

00:02:51.910 --> 00:02:53.860
- So I know I'm meeting this group

00:02:53.860 --> 00:02:55.361
called Guerrilla Mainframe, I know that

00:02:55.361 --> 00:02:56.750
they're a group of black activists

00:02:56.750 --> 00:02:58.420
and that they open carry to protest

00:02:58.420 --> 00:03:01.332
police brutality, and I
know that we're in the South

00:03:01.332 --> 00:03:03.170
which has never had a problem

00:03:03.170 --> 00:03:04.492
with black guys with guns.

00:03:04.492 --> 00:03:05.530
- I think you're gonna be totally fine,

00:03:05.530 --> 00:03:06.530
I wouldn't worry at all.

00:03:06.530 --> 00:03:08.700
- Okay, you have the confidence

00:03:08.700 --> 00:03:11.541
that only a white man
with security can have.

00:03:11.541 --> 00:03:14.209
(metal rubbing)

00:03:14.209 --> 00:03:17.080
- So I am here with Mr. Kobi Libii,

00:03:17.080 --> 00:03:20.050
who is both performer
and writer on Klepper.

00:03:20.050 --> 00:03:21.270
What is Guerrilla Mainframe?

00:03:21.270 --> 00:03:23.820
- So Guerrilla Mainframe is a group

00:03:23.820 --> 00:03:25.880
of black activists based it Texas,

00:03:25.880 --> 00:03:27.150
and they do a bunch of things,

00:03:27.150 --> 00:03:29.350
they do a bunch of community programs,

00:03:29.350 --> 00:03:31.030
in their sort of working
class black community

00:03:31.030 --> 00:03:34.550
in Dallas, but the thing
their most known for

00:03:34.550 --> 00:03:37.290
are these sort of brash, confrontational,

00:03:37.290 --> 00:03:40.750
militant open carry protests
against police brutality.

00:03:40.750 --> 00:03:42.780
So, if you don't know
what some of those phrases

00:03:42.780 --> 00:03:45.340
mean, they take big, conspicuous guns

00:03:45.340 --> 00:03:48.400
out in public and protest
the unjust killing

00:03:48.400 --> 00:03:49.370
of black people by police.

00:03:49.370 --> 00:03:52.970
And so, there's sort of a
militant aesthetic to it,

00:03:52.970 --> 00:03:55.010
so it's a lot of, picture
the Black Panthers,

00:03:55.010 --> 00:03:58.330
picture military fatigues and black gloves

00:03:58.330 --> 00:04:01.708
and, you know, sort of
loud, very sort of direct

00:04:01.708 --> 00:04:02.541
(electric guitar music)

00:04:02.541 --> 00:04:03.900
confrontational chanting, that's

00:04:03.900 --> 00:04:05.532
sort of their style of protest.

00:04:05.532 --> 00:04:07.213
- Whose streets?
- [Group] Our streets!

00:04:07.213 --> 00:04:08.734
- I think this might be them.

00:04:08.734 --> 00:04:10.731
(military drum march)

00:04:10.731 --> 00:04:11.766
Okay, you got a second now?

00:04:11.766 --> 00:04:12.822
- Yeah, yeah, this is time
- All right, awesome.

00:04:12.822 --> 00:04:14.160
Those aren't loaded, right?

00:04:14.160 --> 00:04:14.993
- Huh?

00:04:14.993 --> 00:04:15.826
- Those aren't loaded.

00:04:15.826 --> 00:04:16.659
- No, they are loaded.

00:04:16.659 --> 00:04:17.492
- Oh, okay, yeah.

00:04:17.492 --> 00:04:18.910
- Yes, they're loaded, rocked and ready.

00:04:18.910 --> 00:04:19.743
- Great.
(cymbal roll)

00:04:19.743 --> 00:04:21.530
- What, specifically, were
they protesting that day?

00:04:21.530 --> 00:04:22.950
- So, specifically they were protesting

00:04:22.950 --> 00:04:25.161
the death of a gentleman named Botham Jean

00:04:25.161 --> 00:04:28.750
who was shot to death in his own home

00:04:28.750 --> 00:04:30.760
by an off-duty police officer.

00:04:30.760 --> 00:04:32.270
So, a woman named Amber Guyger

00:04:32.270 --> 00:04:33.280
is an off-duty police officer,

00:04:33.280 --> 00:04:34.850
lived in the same building as Botham Jean

00:04:34.850 --> 00:04:37.570
and went into Botham Jean's apartment,

00:04:37.570 --> 00:04:39.610
and her story is that she believed

00:04:39.610 --> 00:04:40.990
it was her own apartment.

00:04:40.990 --> 00:04:42.680
She walked into Botham Jean's apartment,

00:04:42.680 --> 00:04:45.040
saw a man there, that she believed

00:04:45.040 --> 00:04:49.170
to be a burglar, and
shot him with her weapon,

00:04:49.170 --> 00:04:50.003
and he died.

00:04:50.003 --> 00:04:51.520
- It's an absolutely insane story.

00:04:51.520 --> 00:04:52.620
- It's an insane story, yes.

00:04:52.620 --> 00:04:55.700
So she's white and an
off-duty police officer,

00:04:55.700 --> 00:04:58.080
he's a black man in
line with a lot of other

00:04:58.080 --> 00:05:00.660
unjust killings of unarmed black people,

00:05:00.660 --> 00:05:02.890
this was a particularly
egregious one because

00:05:02.890 --> 00:05:05.180
a dude's just sitting on
his own couch, you know.

00:05:05.180 --> 00:05:09.010
So this was protest about her prosecution

00:05:09.010 --> 00:05:10.620
and what she was charged with,

00:05:10.620 --> 00:05:11.970
and what she wasn't charged with,

00:05:11.970 --> 00:05:14.570
and more broadly raising awareness

00:05:14.570 --> 00:05:15.870
about that killing and

00:05:15.870 --> 00:05:17.502
this sort of epidemic

00:05:17.502 --> 00:05:18.335
(grinding electric guitar)

00:05:18.335 --> 00:05:21.397
of unjust killings of people
of color by the police.

00:05:47.687 --> 00:05:48.590
(cymbal roll)

00:05:48.590 --> 00:05:50.800
- The reason Rakim, who's the leader

00:05:50.800 --> 00:05:53.590
of Guerrilla Mainframe
ended up in, as a figure

00:05:53.590 --> 00:05:55.330
in the national news at all was because

00:05:55.330 --> 00:05:58.680
he was detained for a number of months

00:06:00.322 --> 00:06:02.910
as a result of him being investigated

00:06:02.910 --> 00:06:05.650
under what's called the
Black Identity Extremist

00:06:05.650 --> 00:06:07.880
designation, which is a very shadowy,

00:06:07.880 --> 00:06:10.480
new designation that the FBI created

00:06:10.480 --> 00:06:13.750
to monitor quote-unquote
"Black Identity Extremists"

00:06:13.750 --> 00:06:16.338
which is a nebulously defined, possibly

00:06:16.338 --> 00:06:20.424
nonexistent thing that gives the FBI

00:06:20.424 --> 00:06:24.330
a mandate to follow black activists

00:06:24.330 --> 00:06:26.970
that they are concerned
about for whatever reason.

00:06:26.970 --> 00:06:29.260
And that's distressing to a lot of people

00:06:30.340 --> 00:06:32.710
that care about, you know, civil rights,

00:06:32.710 --> 00:06:34.930
because of COINTELPRO,
there's a long history

00:06:34.930 --> 00:06:38.900
of the FBI doing very troubling monitoring

00:06:38.900 --> 00:06:40.380
of black activists.

00:06:40.380 --> 00:06:43.090
You know, the FBI famously monitored

00:06:43.090 --> 00:06:46.580
Martin Luther King, allegedly sent him

00:06:46.580 --> 00:06:48.130
and a number of other activists

00:06:49.070 --> 00:06:51.980
letters trying to get
them to stop their work,

00:06:51.980 --> 00:06:53.830
encouraging them to kill themselves,

00:06:53.830 --> 00:06:55.780
you know, there's a very troubling history

00:06:55.780 --> 00:06:58.070
of law enforcement, and
the FBI specifically

00:06:58.070 --> 00:07:00.840
monitoring black activists and trying

00:07:00.840 --> 00:07:02.820
to make bad things happen
to black activists.

00:07:02.820 --> 00:07:04.770
Right, so that's the sort
of historical backdrop

00:07:04.770 --> 00:07:05.603
of this.

00:07:05.603 --> 00:07:08.310
And then in 2017 we see
Black Identity Extremist

00:07:08.310 --> 00:07:10.190
program pop the scene, we can't really

00:07:10.190 --> 00:07:12.020
get much context on it, there's no,

00:07:12.020 --> 00:07:13.310
for example there's no equivalent

00:07:13.310 --> 00:07:15.584
White Identity Extremist program to cover

00:07:15.584 --> 00:07:18.900
the white supremacists, and, you know,

00:07:18.900 --> 00:07:21.730
the antisemitic violence,
there's no equivalent

00:07:21.730 --> 00:07:23.930
program to look at that kind of extremism

00:07:23.930 --> 00:07:26.890
but, for some reason
Black Identity Extremism

00:07:26.890 --> 00:07:28.400
is something that the FBI believes,

00:07:28.400 --> 00:07:29.640
or certain parties at the FBI believe

00:07:29.640 --> 00:07:31.010
needs to be monitored in this extreme way.

00:07:31.010 --> 00:07:33.360
Anyway, that's the
backdrop of this and Rakim

00:07:33.360 --> 00:07:35.990
is believed to be the first person

00:07:35.990 --> 00:07:38.162
who's been detained under this

00:07:38.162 --> 00:07:40.140
Black Identity Extremist designation,

00:07:40.140 --> 00:07:42.370
and particularly why he
was on the FBI's radar

00:07:42.370 --> 00:07:44.210
is he's made a number
of very inflammatory,

00:07:44.210 --> 00:07:47.680
very offensive remarks
about law enforcement

00:07:47.680 --> 00:07:49.560
and the death of law enforcement officers

00:07:49.560 --> 00:07:53.415
on Facebook and on Twitter,
and it's explicitly said

00:07:53.415 --> 00:07:56.190
in his trial that the reason he ended up

00:07:56.190 --> 00:07:59.160
on law enforcement's radar
is because of these things.

00:07:59.160 --> 00:08:02.237
Specifically, an FBI,
and this isn't a bit,

00:08:02.237 --> 00:08:05.960
the FBI officer that first flagged him

00:08:05.960 --> 00:08:08.483
found out about him from Alex Jones.

00:08:09.320 --> 00:08:12.450
So the FBI officer watches InfoWars

00:08:12.450 --> 00:08:14.530
and saw InfoWars covering not even

00:08:14.530 --> 00:08:16.240
Rakim's group, but another group

00:08:16.240 --> 00:08:17.570
of black activists marching around.

00:08:17.570 --> 00:08:20.237
And you can imagine the InfoWars
coverage of this, right.

00:08:20.237 --> 00:08:22.790
- I, uh, we watched a lot of that.

00:08:22.790 --> 00:08:24.880
- We spend a lot of time with
that fine gentleman, right,

00:08:24.880 --> 00:08:27.740
but so that's the sort
of level of thinking

00:08:27.740 --> 00:08:30.240
that is going into this, at least

00:08:30.240 --> 00:08:31.850
that's the criticism of it, right.

00:08:31.850 --> 00:08:33.130
So anyway this guy ends up in jail,

00:08:33.130 --> 00:08:35.470
Rakim ends up in jail for five months,

00:08:35.470 --> 00:08:37.410
held without, denied parole, effectively,

00:08:37.410 --> 00:08:38.870
ultimately the charges are dismisses,

00:08:38.870 --> 00:08:40.057
the judge is effectively like,

00:08:40.057 --> 00:08:42.297
"This is nonsense, you can't jail a person

00:08:42.297 --> 00:08:44.470
"because of things they said on Facebook."

00:08:44.470 --> 00:08:47.290
And he was set free,
but the coverage of that

00:08:47.290 --> 00:08:49.360
obviously caused a lot of consternation

00:08:51.658 --> 00:08:52.750
you know, across

00:08:54.210 --> 00:08:56.070
everybody that cares about civil rights.

00:08:56.070 --> 00:08:57.520
So that's the background of this.

00:08:57.520 --> 00:08:59.600
Anyway, we were interested in that group,

00:08:59.600 --> 00:09:01.740
that particular treatment under
the Black Identity Extremist

00:09:01.740 --> 00:09:04.010
designation, what their deal is generally,

00:09:04.010 --> 00:09:06.050
their relationship to gun rights,

00:09:06.050 --> 00:09:07.560
because a black militant group like this

00:09:07.560 --> 00:09:08.613
has a different relationship to gun rights

00:09:08.613 --> 00:09:10.750
than a lot of other progressive groups.

00:09:10.750 --> 00:09:13.720
The difficulty about
trying to tell the story

00:09:13.720 --> 00:09:15.230
of Rakim and Guerrilla Mainframe quickly

00:09:15.230 --> 00:09:16.750
is, ultimately, a difficulty
I think we ran into

00:09:16.750 --> 00:09:19.340
on this show, which is
that some of the statements

00:09:19.340 --> 00:09:21.160
that Rakim and Guerrilla
Mainframe have made

00:09:21.160 --> 00:09:24.750
are so inflammatory that there is gonna be

00:09:24.750 --> 00:09:26.440
a certain segment of the population

00:09:26.440 --> 00:09:28.472
that just shuts down in response to them.

00:09:28.472 --> 00:09:32.098
And one of my concerns
about trying to do that

00:09:32.098 --> 00:09:36.110
was trying to unpack that sort of

00:09:38.300 --> 00:09:39.860
with the detail and care that it deserves

00:09:39.860 --> 00:09:42.050
to be unpacked and, to my sensibility,

00:09:42.050 --> 00:09:46.330
to get people through
the discomfort with that.

00:09:46.330 --> 00:09:47.930
And to be clear, with
this kind of militant

00:09:47.930 --> 00:09:49.490
rhetoric that discomfort
is part of the point.

00:09:49.490 --> 00:09:52.660
- The headlines with Rakim,
rightfully so or not,

00:09:52.660 --> 00:09:54.818
focused on the rhetoric
that was there to get

00:09:54.818 --> 00:09:58.000
attention, that talked
about killing police

00:09:58.910 --> 00:10:00.770
in a flippant manner, "laugh my ass off"

00:10:00.770 --> 00:10:02.670
or "LMAO" I remember was one of the things

00:10:02.670 --> 00:10:03.670
that stood out there.

00:10:03.670 --> 00:10:05.220
And so I recall at the
beginning part of it

00:10:05.220 --> 00:10:06.440
it was like "Oh, it's tough."

00:10:06.440 --> 00:10:07.460
As we're choosing things to put

00:10:07.460 --> 00:10:10.060
on television, is this
the kind of thing, are we

00:10:10.060 --> 00:10:12.460
signal boosting a group
that is more problematic

00:10:12.460 --> 00:10:13.790
than it is helpful?

00:10:13.790 --> 00:10:15.420
I remember that being part of the early

00:10:15.420 --> 00:10:16.600
discussions we had there.

00:10:16.600 --> 00:10:19.277
And I think, like, as this story evolved

00:10:19.277 --> 00:10:20.800
we did find this day when they were

00:10:20.800 --> 00:10:21.633
having the protest.

00:10:21.633 --> 00:10:25.030
