00:29:52.978 --> 00:29:53.990
and it's like there's
all these studies about

00:29:53.990 --> 00:29:55.750
how so much communication
is not about language

00:29:55.750 --> 00:29:56.710
and what you're literally
saying but just like

00:29:56.710 --> 00:29:59.320
the vibe you're sending out.

00:29:59.320 --> 00:30:00.960
It's why everybody
thinks we're so charming,

00:30:00.960 --> 00:30:02.600
it's not our words it's our energy.

00:30:02.600 --> 00:30:03.880
- Thank you.

00:30:03.880 --> 00:30:06.210
- But there's the nonverbal
energy I'm getting

00:30:06.210 --> 00:30:10.570
from that context is so deeply hostile

00:30:10.570 --> 00:30:13.970
and deeply uncomfortable in a way that is

00:30:13.970 --> 00:30:18.970
very hard to communicate
to people who aren't

00:30:20.400 --> 00:30:23.070
attenuated to hear that
discomfort as danger.

00:30:23.070 --> 00:30:23.903
Does that make sense?

00:30:23.903 --> 00:30:25.820
Because when I feel that
discomfort in a group

00:30:25.820 --> 00:30:27.243
of white people, I'm like "Oh, shit."

00:30:27.243 --> 00:30:30.197
I am like "I need to be aware because

00:30:30.197 --> 00:30:31.220
"I am in trouble."

00:30:31.220 --> 00:30:33.700
Because that level of concern

00:30:33.700 --> 00:30:34.963
from a police officer is something

00:30:34.963 --> 00:30:36.210
that could kill me, that level of

00:30:36.210 --> 00:30:37.810
concern is gonna get
the police called on me,

00:30:37.810 --> 00:30:39.830
that level of concern is
gonna get me into a conflict

00:30:39.830 --> 00:30:41.240
in my nice middle class
restaurant that I'm in,

00:30:41.240 --> 00:30:44.420
you know, and so it's
perhaps a hyper-awareness

00:30:44.420 --> 00:30:47.610
to it but that discomfort is a real thing,

00:30:47.610 --> 00:30:49.060
and that's very much what we got

00:30:49.060 --> 00:30:51.570
when we crossed over into
that white community.

00:30:51.570 --> 00:30:52.403
- That totally makes sense.

00:30:52.403 --> 00:30:54.882
I guess my thought in that is,

00:30:54.882 --> 00:30:57.640
that's also the intended
response, correct?

00:30:57.640 --> 00:30:58.473
- Sure, yeah.

00:30:58.473 --> 00:31:01.260
- So is that a successful form of protest?

00:31:01.260 --> 00:31:03.540
In the fact that you are able to see that,

00:31:03.540 --> 00:31:06.940
in the fact that you
have some white people

00:31:06.940 --> 00:31:07.817
going to a football game who are like,

00:31:07.817 --> 00:31:09.370
"Holy shit, what is this? What is this?"

00:31:09.370 --> 00:31:12.580
and then they're forced to
have that conversation then.

00:31:12.580 --> 00:31:14.780
Like, no matter what, if I'm going

00:31:14.780 --> 00:31:15.613
to a football game and a bunch of people

00:31:15.613 --> 00:31:18.200
are coming up with guns,
I'm gonna talk about it.

00:31:18.200 --> 00:31:19.610
And then if a camera comes up to me,

00:31:19.610 --> 00:31:20.443
I'm probably gonna be like,

00:31:20.443 --> 00:31:21.630
"Uh, I wasn't talking about it."

00:31:21.630 --> 00:31:24.710
Now, I don't doubt that there is a giant

00:31:24.710 --> 00:31:26.653
racial component there, of course,

00:31:27.490 --> 00:31:29.370
but I'm wondering, is
that how that situation

00:31:29.370 --> 00:31:30.313
is going to play out?

00:31:30.313 --> 00:31:32.330
- I think it's as much about, you know,

00:31:32.330 --> 00:31:34.754
angry anti-police chants and a bunch of

00:31:34.754 --> 00:31:37.830
loud black guys being loud and direct

00:31:37.830 --> 00:31:39.060
and confrontational and black

00:31:39.060 --> 00:31:41.520
as it is the weapons on their backs.

00:31:41.520 --> 00:31:43.170
In terms of whether or
not that's successful,

00:31:43.170 --> 00:31:44.350
I think it's a really good question,

00:31:44.350 --> 00:31:46.790
and it's an audience question, right?

00:31:46.790 --> 00:31:48.430
So there's the one conversation about

00:31:48.430 --> 00:31:49.940
it being nourishing to a community

00:31:49.940 --> 00:31:51.990
that feels stepped on, and then

00:31:51.990 --> 00:31:52.950
there's a conversation about, okay

00:31:52.950 --> 00:31:56.420
what are we doing with
this kind of rhetoric?

00:31:56.420 --> 00:31:59.470
One of the functions of
this kind of militant

00:31:59.470 --> 00:32:01.367
posturing, rhetorically, is to say,

00:32:01.367 --> 00:32:05.077
"Okay, well, if you are comfortable

00:32:05.077 --> 00:32:07.817
"with this kind of
violence being done to us,

00:32:07.817 --> 00:32:10.487
"what do you feel, like come with me on

00:32:10.487 --> 00:32:12.997
"the empathetic exercise of imagining

00:32:12.997 --> 00:32:15.077
"if this kind of violence came back to you

00:32:15.077 --> 00:32:16.490
"and your community."

00:32:16.490 --> 00:32:21.270
And the level of discomfort
that white people

00:32:21.270 --> 00:32:23.108
feel when they hear somebody like

00:32:23.108 --> 00:32:26.310
Rakim talk so cavalierly about the death

00:32:26.310 --> 00:32:27.930
of white police officers, that level

00:32:27.930 --> 00:32:30.590
of discomfort is the level of discomfort

00:32:30.590 --> 00:32:32.399
a mainstream white audience should feel

00:32:32.399 --> 00:32:34.210
every single time they hear about

00:32:34.210 --> 00:32:35.440
a black person being killed.

00:32:35.440 --> 00:32:38.630
And I think the criticism,
the most generous,

00:32:38.630 --> 00:32:41.210
sophisticated reading of this vocabulary

00:32:41.210 --> 00:32:42.682
of protest is that, okay well,

00:32:42.682 --> 00:32:45.730
obviously, nonviolent protests,

00:32:45.730 --> 00:32:48.460
Black Lives Matter, all these other modes

00:32:48.460 --> 00:32:50.570
of trying to communicate
how fundamentally,

00:32:50.570 --> 00:32:53.320
viscerally unjust the situation we're in,

00:32:53.320 --> 00:32:56.980
all that's not really
getting the job done,

00:32:56.980 --> 00:33:00.320
and so I'm going to try to reflect back

00:33:00.320 --> 00:33:02.950
the kind of violence we
are experiencing at you

00:33:02.950 --> 00:33:05.213
and see if that shakes anything.

00:33:06.830 --> 00:33:08.740
So, to your point, it is designed

00:33:08.740 --> 00:33:10.750
to make people, I think, uncomfortable,

00:33:10.750 --> 00:33:13.270
and I think the question
is whether or not,

00:33:13.270 --> 00:33:14.900
is what we then do with that discomfort.

00:33:14.900 --> 00:33:16.850
What does that discomfort mean?

00:33:16.850 --> 00:33:20.300
And do I have a similar
level of discomfort

00:33:20.300 --> 00:33:21.917
about the injustices
they're complaining about?

00:33:21.917 --> 00:33:24.870
- The argument that you make is, I think,

00:33:24.870 --> 00:33:25.980
and incredible argument, and I think,

00:33:25.980 --> 00:33:28.530
like, what you're asking
for is an engagement

00:33:28.530 --> 00:33:31.780
with a white community
that is not engaging

00:33:31.780 --> 00:33:33.660
with a community that is under duress,

00:33:33.660 --> 00:33:34.960
that is feeling that this kind of stress,

00:33:34.960 --> 00:33:37.717
and has felt this kind of violence for

00:33:37.717 --> 00:33:40.190
a hundred years, but the articulation

00:33:40.190 --> 00:33:42.840
of that in the moment is,
obviously it's the guns

00:33:42.840 --> 00:33:43.690
to grab attention.

00:33:43.690 --> 00:33:46.940
It is chants, it's chants,
it's "Oink oink, bang bang."

00:33:46.940 --> 00:33:49.500
Like, the chants are directed at police

00:33:49.500 --> 00:33:51.340
- Yeah, that's about killing police.

00:33:51.340 --> 00:33:52.173
- 100 percent.

00:33:52.173 --> 00:33:53.050
- That is a chant about killing police.

00:33:53.050 --> 00:33:54.750
- So I feel like you
have, there are definitely

00:33:54.750 --> 00:33:55.740
people on the right,
there are people who are

00:33:55.740 --> 00:33:58.200
very critical of Guerrilla Mainframe

00:33:58.200 --> 00:33:59.560
specifically because of their tactics

00:33:59.560 --> 00:34:03.293
because of the lines that they cross.

00:34:04.400 --> 00:34:06.160
Again, this is the
conversations that we were

00:34:06.160 --> 00:34:07.843
having, like, when you are there

00:34:07.843 --> 00:34:09.250
and you are seeing that happen,

00:34:09.250 --> 00:34:11.890
and you're having that emotional journey

00:34:11.890 --> 00:34:14.170
to see how people are reacting to that,

00:34:14.170 --> 00:34:16.370
are you frustrated with the means

00:34:16.370 --> 00:34:18.360
that they're using to elicit that reaction

00:34:18.360 --> 00:34:21.078
or do you find this reaction,

00:34:21.078 --> 00:34:24.000
I understand that it's a
reaction out of necessity,

00:34:24.000 --> 00:34:26.680
but how comfortable are you with

00:34:26.680 --> 00:34:28.333
that form of protest?

00:34:33.530 --> 00:34:37.503
- It's difficult to, I have my ambivalence

00:34:37.503 --> 00:34:38.480
about it, right?

00:34:38.480 --> 00:34:43.480
Like I don't, I have my
ambivalence about it, I think.

00:34:43.800 --> 00:34:47.470
But, my sort of first order, before I can

00:34:47.470 --> 00:34:50.020
engage with my own personal ambivalence

00:34:50.020 --> 00:34:54.510
about it, I have, sort
of first and foremost,

00:34:54.510 --> 00:34:58.860
the work of asking other people,

00:34:58.860 --> 00:35:00.350
asking white people, effectively,

00:35:00.350 --> 00:35:02.423
to engage with it honestly,

00:35:03.310 --> 00:35:05.040
and it's one of the frustrations

00:35:05.040 --> 00:35:06.530
about working on this piece, honestly,

00:35:06.530 --> 00:35:09.570
is that I do have real questions

00:35:09.570 --> 00:35:12.020
about this group
specifically, and I do have

00:35:12.020 --> 00:35:13.520
real questions about whether or not

00:35:13.520 --> 00:35:15.580
this mode of protest moves the needle

00:35:15.580 --> 00:35:16.413
in a positive way.

00:35:16.413 --> 00:35:17.320
The same questions I had about

00:35:17.320 --> 00:35:19.650
the Black Panther Party, and militant

00:35:19.650 --> 00:35:21.780
Marcus Garvey groups on
back through the history

00:35:21.780 --> 00:35:22.850
of black people.

00:35:22.850 --> 00:35:25.060
But again, to me that's sort of

00:35:25.060 --> 00:35:29.300
a second-order problem,
because the first-order

00:35:29.300 --> 00:35:33.410
problem is asking for meaningful

00:35:33.410 --> 00:35:35.550
engagement with the thing that it is.

00:35:35.550 --> 00:35:40.550
And I find that, and I
found working on this piece

00:35:41.090 --> 00:35:45.010
that the discomfort that is produced

00:35:45.010 --> 00:35:48.940
by the rhetoric is so loud that it

00:35:50.361 --> 00:35:51.803
shuts white people down.

00:35:53.092 --> 00:35:56.390
- But is the actions,
are they disqualifying?

00:35:56.390 --> 00:35:57.223
- In what sense?

00:35:57.223 --> 00:35:58.056
- Well, I think--

00:35:58.056 --> 00:35:59.760
- It's language, no, it's language,

00:35:59.760 --> 00:36:00.607
you know what I mean?

00:36:00.607 --> 00:36:02.900
- But at some point somebody shuts off,

00:36:02.900 --> 00:36:05.240
and we're aware of when you push something

00:36:05.240 --> 00:36:10.060
so somebody shuts off,
and I think the reticence

00:36:10.060 --> 00:36:12.960
that you have if people
hear "Oink oink, bang bang."

00:36:12.960 --> 00:36:16.780
If you hear something
online that is making fun

00:36:16.780 --> 00:36:19.210
of police officers who are
dead and their families,

00:36:19.210 --> 00:36:20.913
and you challenged Rakim on that.

00:36:23.450 --> 00:36:25.240
Is that a line that is
crossed at which point

00:36:25.240 --> 00:36:27.200
you are not going to be heard because

00:36:27.200 --> 00:36:29.620
you have crossed that now delegitimizes

00:36:29.620 --> 00:36:30.820
the argument that you have?

00:36:30.820 --> 00:36:31.990
- It's a larger conversation about decorum

00:36:31.990 --> 00:36:34.470
in politics, about decorum, you know,

00:36:34.470 --> 00:36:37.035
and propriety, and there are communities

00:36:37.035 --> 00:36:39.440
that feel like they don't have the luxury

00:36:39.440 --> 00:36:41.150
of being polite because they're dying.

00:36:41.150 --> 00:36:44.510
I do have concerns, I often
wish groups like this,

00:36:44.510 --> 00:36:46.310
and I very much include
the Black Panther Party

00:36:46.310 --> 00:36:49.440
in this, were more
thoughtful and deliberate

00:36:49.440 --> 00:36:53.560
about how this kind of
confrontational messaging

00:36:53.560 --> 00:36:57.010
can be useful and can
be counterproductive.

00:36:57.010 --> 00:37:00.910
Like, I almost always
want groups like this

00:37:00.910 --> 00:37:02.730
to be a little more sophisticated

00:37:02.730 --> 00:37:04.550
with how they wield the powerful tools

00:37:04.550 --> 00:37:05.460
that they're wielding.

00:37:05.460 --> 00:37:07.780
But again that's like,
that's let's shut the door

00:37:07.780 --> 00:37:09.453
and have that conversation separately.

00:37:10.446 --> 00:37:13.960
Because to me that's an abdication

00:37:13.960 --> 00:37:16.260
of responsibility as
a mainstream audience,

00:37:16.260 --> 00:37:18.510
and it's an abdication of responsibility

00:37:18.510 --> 00:37:20.137
as white listeners to say,

00:37:20.137 --> 00:37:22.878
"Okay, well you haven't
packaged this for me

00:37:22.878 --> 00:37:24.827
"in a way that makes me comfortable,

00:37:24.827 --> 00:37:27.527
"therefore, I have permission to keep

00:37:27.527 --> 00:37:28.440
"shutting the door on this."

00:37:28.440 --> 00:37:30.500
It's a less conservative version

00:37:30.500 --> 00:37:32.090
of the conversation about
Kaepernick and kneeling

00:37:32.090 --> 00:37:33.897
which is like "Oh, I get
that police brutality

00:37:33.897 --> 00:37:35.277
"is is a thing you wanna talk about,

00:37:35.277 --> 00:37:36.887
"but the way you're doing it,

00:37:36.887 --> 00:37:40.477
"the nature of this protest turns me off

00:37:40.477 --> 00:37:42.447
"so I'm not going to
engage with the substance

00:37:42.447 --> 00:37:43.897
"of your criticism because the manner

00:37:43.897 --> 00:37:45.200
"of your speech is shutting me down."

00:37:45.200 --> 00:37:46.620
It's a similar criticism, right?

00:37:46.620 --> 00:37:49.390
- But I would say, I remember watching

00:37:49.390 --> 00:37:51.910
your interview with Rakim and,

00:37:51.910 --> 00:37:53.250
I think we even watched this together,

00:37:53.250 --> 00:37:54.217
and I think, like,

00:37:54.217 --> 00:37:57.010
- I remember this I remember very clearly.

00:37:57.010 --> 00:38:00.598
- You ask him about his Facebook posts,

00:38:00.598 --> 00:38:03.527
and you say, like "These police officers

00:38:03.527 --> 00:38:06.687
"were killed in Dallas, and you said LMAO

00:38:06.687 --> 00:38:08.017
"smiley face."

00:38:08.860 --> 00:38:11.960
And Rakim was like "Oh,
yeah, I laughed, I laughed."

00:38:11.960 --> 00:38:13.593
Rakim owned it.

00:38:13.593 --> 00:38:14.426
(grinding electric guitar)

00:38:14.426 --> 00:38:15.259
And he was joyous at a few moments,

00:38:15.259 --> 00:38:17.460
and for me, I'm like "Fuck this guy."

00:38:17.460 --> 00:38:18.830
- Do you stand by those statements?

00:38:18.830 --> 00:38:21.740
- I didn't say those
officers as individuals

00:38:21.740 --> 00:38:22.770
deserved what they got,

00:38:22.770 --> 00:38:26.237
I said the police
department deserved that.

00:38:26.237 --> 00:38:27.510
- So, just to be clear, I'm pretty sure

00:38:27.510 --> 00:38:29.200
the exact quote was "They
deserve what they got."

00:38:29.200 --> 00:38:32.080
and I think it was, "LMAO" afterwards.

00:38:32.080 --> 00:38:34.450
- Yes, and I was laughing, and I'm still

00:38:34.450 --> 00:38:38.400
laughing today, just like
they're laughing at me, right?

00:38:38.400 --> 00:38:41.060
Because as a black person what you hear

00:38:41.060 --> 00:38:46.060
is Trayvon Martin, is
Michael Brown, Tamir Rice.

00:38:46.790 --> 00:38:49.500
Eventually at some point
it become frustrating.

00:38:49.500 --> 00:38:53.260
- How can you, then,
turn around and celebrate

00:38:53.260 --> 00:38:54.810
other people, going through the pain

00:38:54.810 --> 00:38:56.020
of losing people that they love?

00:38:56.020 --> 00:38:59.550
- Just like America celebrated Hiroshima

00:38:59.550 --> 00:39:02.940
and Nagasaki, after
Pearl Harbor, you know.

00:39:02.940 --> 00:39:06.870
It's just, you guys get
to grieve, for a change.

00:39:06.870 --> 00:39:09.460
- Do you have any intention
of doing something

00:39:09.460 --> 00:39:10.293
like what he did?

00:39:10.293 --> 00:39:11.126
- No.

00:39:11.126 --> 00:39:14.260
Killing police officers is not gonna stop

00:39:14.260 --> 00:39:18.270
police brutality, if anything
it's gonna encourage it.

00:39:18.270 --> 00:39:19.103
You know--

00:39:19.103 --> 00:39:20.020
- But couldn't you say the same thing

00:39:20.020 --> 00:39:21.510
about your statements, though?

00:39:21.510 --> 00:39:24.420
- I wanna be provocative
enough to get their attention.

00:39:24.420 --> 00:39:25.253
- Okay.
(cymbal roll)

00:39:25.253 --> 00:39:26.727
- I was like, "This
negates everything he did

00:39:26.727 --> 00:39:27.890
"up until this point."

00:39:27.890 --> 00:39:31.597
And also I'm like, "I
feel weird about putting

00:39:31.597 --> 00:39:33.587
"this guy on television because of that

00:39:33.587 --> 00:39:35.490
"aggressive stance."

00:39:35.490 --> 00:39:36.890
Also I feel protective, because I do think

00:39:36.890 --> 00:39:38.170
I agree with the things that you're saying

00:39:38.170 --> 00:39:39.920
in the attention that they're bringing,

00:39:39.920 --> 00:39:41.207
but I'm like, "This is delegitimizing

00:39:41.207 --> 00:39:42.470
"all the stuff he did before."

00:39:42.470 --> 00:39:45.700
Like, in order to try to amplify

00:39:45.700 --> 00:39:48.400
the actual story, which,
at that point, to me

00:39:48.400 --> 00:39:51.190
felt like drawing attention
to police violence

00:39:51.190 --> 00:39:52.440
against African-American communities,

00:39:52.440 --> 00:39:53.960
specifically in Texas, it's like

00:39:53.960 --> 00:39:56.330
you have a guy who's laughing about

00:39:56.330 --> 00:39:57.780
cops getting killed, and like,

00:39:57.780 --> 00:39:59.848
guess what the stories gonna be,

00:39:59.848 --> 00:40:01.190
the stories gonna be
the guy who's laughing

00:40:01.190 --> 00:40:02.470
at cops getting killed.

00:40:02.470 --> 00:40:03.800
We want it to be about something else,

00:40:03.800 --> 00:40:05.630
we can't amplify that part of that story.

00:40:05.630 --> 00:40:06.960
- It's interesting, and I appreciate

00:40:06.960 --> 00:40:09.033
your bringing up that, you
watching it for the first time,

00:40:09.033 --> 00:40:10.621
because I was really struck by that,

00:40:10.621 --> 00:40:14.560
that was a striking
moment just in the process

00:40:14.560 --> 00:40:17.450
of making that for me because I've never

00:40:17.450 --> 00:40:21.270
seen you react so
negatively to an interview

00:40:21.270 --> 00:40:22.377
subject before.

00:40:24.530 --> 00:40:25.790
My experience of it was
that you were really

00:40:25.790 --> 00:40:29.610
quite reviled by that and
really quite disgusted

00:40:29.610 --> 00:40:31.810
by that in a way that
I think is, is, that's

00:40:32.670 --> 00:40:34.384
your personal reaction
and is very appropriate

00:40:34.384 --> 00:40:36.210
in that respect.

00:40:36.210 --> 00:40:38.310
But I remember being
very surprised by that

00:40:38.310 --> 00:40:42.120
because I don't have,
I challenge him on it

00:40:42.120 --> 00:40:42.953
in the interview.

00:40:42.953 --> 00:40:47.755
I find those statements
at the very least clumsy,

00:40:49.120 --> 00:40:51.263
and at the very most, immoral.

00:40:52.960 --> 00:40:57.960
But they don't elicit the
same real repulsion for me,

00:41:01.720 --> 00:41:06.093
and I do think that is
a racialized difference,

